03650nmm a2200541Ia 9780520913783DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20231992cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209137837 a10.1525/97805209137832doi  a(DE-B1597)543791  a(OCoLC)1149476743  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aJC474b.J695 1993 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a321.922231 aJowitt, Ken, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNew World Disorder :bThe Leninist Extinction /cKen Jowitt.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (345 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCommunism, or as Ken Jowitt prefers, Leninism, has attracted, repelled, mystified, and terrified millions for nearly a century. In his brilliant, timely, and controversial study, New World Disorder, Jowitt identifies and interprets the extraordinary character of Leninist regimes, their political corruption, extinction, and highly unsettling legacy.Earlier attempts to grasp the essence of Leninism have treated the Soviet experience as either a variant of or alien to Western history, an approach that robs Leninism of much of its intriguing novelty. Jowitt instead takes a "polytheist" approach, Weberian in tenor and terms, comparing the Leninist to the liberal experience in the West, rather than assimilating it or alienating it.Approaching the Leninist phenomenon in these terms and spirit emphasizes how powerful the imperatives set by the West for the rest of the world are as sources of emulation, assimilation, rejection, and adaptation; how unyielding premodern forms of identification, organization, and action are; how novel, powerful, and dangerous charisma as a mode of organized indentity and action can be.The progression from essay to essay is lucid and coherent. The first six essays reject the fundamental assumptions about social change that inform the work of modernization theorists. Written between 1974 and 1990, they are, we know now, startingly prescient. The last three essays, written in early 1991, are the most controversial: they will be called alarmist, pessimistic, apocalyptic. They challenge the complacent, optimistic, and self-serving belief that the world is being decisively shaped in the image of the West—that the end of history is at hand.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunismxCommunist countries. 0aCommunism. 0aCommunist state. 0aPolitical culturexCommunist countries. 0aPolitical culturezCommunist countries. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520913783?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520913783423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520913783/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles